**Steps to Reproduce**
Add a 'change' event handler for a Backbone Model instance.
Make a change to model attribute, change event handler is called and some exception occurs in the handler.
Again, make a change to model attribute. No 'change' event handlers are called.

Code to demonstrate this.
```javascript
var model = new Backbone.Model();

var changeHandler = function() {
    console.log("name changed to: " + model.get('name'));
};
Backbone.Events.listenTo(model, 'change', changeHandler);

model.set('name', 'sachin');
// prints "name changed to: sachin" on console
model.set('name', 'virat');
// prints "name changed to: virat" on console

var model2 = new Backbone.Model();

var changeHandler = function() {
    console.log("name changed to: " + model2.get('name'));
    a.log("model changed"); // will throw an exception. a is not defined.
};
Backbone.Events.listenTo(model2, 'change', changeHandler);

model2.set('name', 'Sachin');
// prints "name changed to: Sachin" on console. Also exception occurs inside change handler

model2.set('name', 'Virat');
// nothing is printed. model change handler is not called.
model2.set('name', 'Rohit');
// nothing is printed. model change handler is not called.
```

**Analysis:**
Inside Model set function, this.trigger is called and if Exception is thrown in handlers, this._changing is never set to false and on subsequent model changes, 'change' event will not be triggered. 
```javascript
if (changing) return this;
            if (!silent) {
                while (this._pending) {
                    this._pending = false;
                    this.trigger('change', this, options);
                }
            }
            this._pending = false;
            this._changing = false;
            return this;
```
A developer's code should never break behaviour of a framwork. Smilarly subsequent changes to model should trigger 'change' event on model. 

**Solution**
Should wrap trigger logic around try/finally block ensuring this._changing and this._pending are set to false.

    this.model.set("title", this.$el.find('input').val()); // new value
    this.model.set("text", this.$el.find('textarea').val()); // value not changed

    var changed = this.model.changedAttributes();
    console.log(changed) // changed is false!


  but if

    this.model.set({
      title: this.$el.find('input').val(), // new value
      text: this.$el.find('textarea').val() // value not changed
    })

    var changed = this.model.changedAttributes();
    console.log(changed) // changed is valid!

