SUBJECT: Problem when Model and Collection each have "parse" methods.

By Alexander Danel
2016-May-27

When both "Collection" and its underlying "Model" each have their own "parse" 
method defined, an attempt to do "collection.fetch()" causes a problem.
The retrieved data is processed first by "collection.parse()",
and then a little bit later the processed data is passed to 
"model.parse()", but the second parse fails, because the data
is cooked, not raw.

The reason to have a "parse" method on the Model is because I do sometimes
instantiate the Model as a singleton, not just as a member of the collection.
In other words, although the model gets instantiated automatically by the
collection in some parts of my program, I also want to sometimes manually
instantiate it.  (Automatic bulk instantiations versus manual singleton
instantiations.)

The workaround, for me, I suppose, is to define two different Model classes 
that are otherwise identical except that one would have "parse" and the other 
would not.  But, that's not elegant.  The intention is that they should both
the bulk and singleton instantiations should be of one class.

PROPOSAL: It is my understanding that the "options" to an instantiation can 
include a value for "parse" that is true/false.   Therefore, I suggest that
this option be used when the Collection instantiates a Model, temporarily
setting "parse:false".

