A fairly common pattern I find myself typing when working with Backbone models involves code like this:

```
//iterating
model.set('totalCount', model.get('totalCount') + 1);
model.set('team1Count', model.get('team1Count') + 1);

//updating a max
model.set('maximum', _.max([model.get('maximum'), newValue]));

//updating according to an algorithm

let cost = model.get('cost');
if (!_.isFinite(cost)) {
  //if we haven't calculated the cost yet, do so now
  cost = calculateCost(model);  
} 
model.set('cost', applyCouponCode(cost, couponCode));
```

There's nothing wrong with these examples, but I find myself writing these "get-modify-set" chunks of code a lot.  I think this experience could pretty easily be made nicer.  I'm picturing an `update` method on model that would make the above examples look like this.

```
//iterating
model.update(['totalCount', "team1Count"], count => count + 1);

//updating a max
model.update('maximum', max => _.max([max, newValue]));

//updating according to an algorithm

model.update('cost', function (cost, key, _model) {
  if (!_.isFinite(cost)) {
    //if we haven't calculated the cost yet, do so now
    cost = calculateCost(_model);  
  } 
  return applyCouponCode(cost, couponCode)
});
```

The update function would likely take 3 options: `attrs`, `transform`, `options`. 

`attrs`\- an attribute name or array of attribute names to apply the transform to
`transform` - a function (defaults to _.identity) that will be passed 3 arguments `value`, `key`, `model` and will return the new value for each attribute it is run against
`options` - these would be options that would be passed through to the underlying set call that would result from the update

I'm opening this issue basically to gauge interest in having a function like this as part of Backbone core and to receive feedback.  If there is interest I'd be happy to open a PR to explore further.

