Say my window.location is `/root?foo=bar` and my browser is IE7.

I call `Backbone.history.start({root: '/root', pushState: true});`

That turns the location to `/root#`, but it should turn the location to `/root#?foo=bar`.

This happens because `this.getFragment()` initially computes the fragment as '' (empty string) because `this._hasPushState` is `false` and `this._wantsHashChange` is `true`, so `History#getFragment` just return `this.getHash()`.

Then since we are on oldIE, `History#start` calls `this.navigate(fragment)`. But this fragment is empty.

I currently work around this problem in my specific case with this hack:

```
    var root = '/candidate/list',
        isExplorer = /msie [\w.]+/,
        docMode = document.documentMode,
        oldIE = (
            isExplorer.exec(navigator.userAgent.toLowerCase()) &&
            (!docMode || docMode <= 7)),
        location = window.location;
    if (location.search && !location.hash && oldIE) {
        location.replace(root + '#' + location.search);
        return;
    }
    Backbone.history.start({pushState: true, root: root});
```

