I find myself often wanting to pass a promise for a model to a view, as this makes the job of rendering progress indicators really simple:

```
render: function () {
  if (this.model.then) {
    this.model.then(function(model) {
      this.model = model;
      this.render();
    }.bind(this));
    // render a spinner
  } else {
    // we have a model and can render it here
  }
}
```

To make this really simple, it would be nice to do this:

```
var view = new MyView({
  model: someModel.fetch()
});
```

The only problem is, the promise from `fetch` resolves to the plain data from the server, so you have to do this:

```
var view = new MyView({
  model: someModel.fetch(function (model) {
    return someModel;
  })
});
```

Obviously just changing the resolution of the fetch promise is going to break all sorts of things. So, I propose either an option the `fetch` call that changes what is resolved, or another method:

```
fetchModel: function () {
  return this.fetch().then(function () {
    return this;
  }.bind(this));
}
```

It would probably need an appropriate way of handling failures, and also the name isn't great. But the general principle stands: `fetch` currently resolves to a pretty pointless value.

