Because both `id` and `cid` are used as the keys of `_byId`, there's an implicit assumption that no model's `id` will equal the `cid` of any other model in the same collection. Breaking this assumption causes very strange behavior:

```
var model1 = new Backbone.Model()  // model1.cid = 'c1'
var model2 = new Backbone.Model({id: 'c1'})
var collection1 = new Backbone.Collection([model1, model2])
var collection2 = new Backbone.Collection([model2, model1])
```

In this case, `collection1` will only contain `model1`, and `collection2` will only contain `model2`.

This doesn't seem like an unrealistic edge case to me. I think the `_byId` hash should be broken up into separate `_byId` and `_byCid` hashes, with the `Collection::get` behavior made explicit to favor ids over cids:

```
return this._byId[obj] || this._byCid[obj] || this._byId[obj.id] || this._byCid[obj.cid];
```

In 1.\* View will change arguments[0] from null to an empty object, so the initialize() will be called with {} instead of null (which breaks some implementations that check for null):
var View = Backbone.View = function(options) {
    this.cid = _.uniqueId('view');
    options || (options = {});      // <------ options(arguments[0]) is set to {} if it was null
    _.extend(this, _.pick(options, viewOptions));
    this._ensureElement();
    this.initialize.apply(this, arguments);  // <----- initialize is called with the new value
    this.delegateEvents();
  };

