Let's say we have a model like this:

<pre>
    var Book = Backbone.Model.extend({
        defaults: function() {
            return {
                'title': '',
                'authors': [],
                'publish_info': {
                    'publisher': '',
                    'isbn': '',
                    'year': 0,
                    'month': 0
                }
            };
        },
        initialize: function() {
            this.on('change', function(model, options) {
                console.log('change');
            });
        }
    });
</pre>


Now in the above model, I literally have NO way to change the properties inside the `publisher_info` object which will also fire the `change` event.

I can do something like this:

```
b.get('publish_info')['year'] = 2012;
```

But this defeats the purpose of using models -- no change event is fired.

Similarly, I have no way to change elements inside the `authors` array.

```
var b = new Book();

// works fine
b.set('title', 'test');
```

But:

```
// replaces the entire 'publish_info' object instead of "updating" it
b.set('publish_info', {'year':2012});

b.set('authors', ['mike']);

// this replaces the entire array, and the author 'mike' is vanished
b.set('authors', ['jane']);
```

Hence,  we need a way to set object properties and array elements.

What we can do is something like this:

`set` should `_.extend` the object instead of replacing it. Pass `{'replace':true}` as an option to replace, which is `false` by default

```
// extend
b.set('publish_info', {'year':2012});

// replace
b.set('publish_info', {'year':2012}, {'replace':true});
```

Similarly, for arrays

```
// appends
b.set('authors', ['jane']);

// prepends
b.set('authors', ['jane'], {'at': 0});

// replaces
b.set('authors', ['jane'], {'replace': true});
```

