I want to bring up the idea of forwarding event calls between different backbone objects (e.g. for bubbling up event calls).

Currently you will have to do something similar to this to forward events:

```
var ListView = Backbone.View.extend({

    tagName: "ul",

    className: "list",

    initialize: function() {
        this.view = new ItemView();
        this.view.on('show', this.showItem, this);
    },

    showItem: function(model) {
        this.trigger('show:item', model);
    }

});

```

The downside of this implementation is that you have to define lots of function which actually do not have any real logic inside.
The other way to use an anonymous function is not that readable:

```
var ListView = Backbone.View.extend({

    tagName: "ul",

    className: "list",

    initialize: function() {
        this.view = new ItemView();
        this.view.on('show', function(model) {
            this.trigger('show:item', model);
        }, this);
    }

});

```

My wish would be some api change for the on method which would allow something like this:

```
var ListView = Backbone.View.extend({

    tagName: "ul",

    className: "list",

    initialize: function() {
        this.view = new ItemView();
        this.view.on('show', 'show:item', this);
        // or alternative:
        this.view.forward('show', 'show:item', this);
    }

});

```

The downside would now be that the event system would be somehow coupled to another context where there is no guarantee if the new context supports the event api. However it would really improve code which has to bubble up lots of different event chains....

Regards, 
