In views you can pass custom options via the `options` object: And then within the view, you can access the options as `this.options` everywhere:

``` javascript
var MyView = Backbone.View.extend({
    initialize: function() {
        var value = this.options.value;
    },

    somethingElse: function() {
        doSomething(this.options.value);
    }
});
```

This proves to be very useful for passing all kinds of options to configure the views.

Now, in collections, there is a similar functionality available (per docs)

`new Collection([models], [options])`

But strangely, you can not access those options via `this.options`. In order to access these options, you need to accept an `options` argument in your `initialize` function:

``` JavaScript
var MyColl = Backbone.Collection.extend({
    initialize: function(models, options) {
        var value = options.value;
    }
});
```

You can do something like this:

``` JavaScript
var MyColl = Backbone.Collection.extend({
    initialize: function(models, options) {
        this.options = options;
    }
});
```

But I think if it behaved like views so that we don't have to manually set the `options` object on `this` -- it would feel more consistent.

