A common pattern is to have a view that binds to a model; when the view is removed it should clean up its listeners using unbind. One problem with the current way Backbone does things is that you have to do something like this to handle things (pseudocode):

My view class:

initialize: function(){
   this.changeListener_ = this.render.bind(this);
   this.model.bind('change:revision', this.changeListener_);
},

render: function(){
  // ...
},

remove: function(){
   this.model.unbind('change:revision', this.changeListener_);
}

---

Most of the time you want to bind your Backbone listeners to an instance. However, in order to safely unbind them you have to keep an instance variable around for them to truly unbind them. This gets gross and leads to code clutter.

If the bind and unbind methods allowed an optional instance variable as their third argument, this goes away and the code becomes much cleaner (pseudocode):

My view class:

initialize: function(){
   this.model.bind('change:revision', this.render, this);
},

render: function(){
  // ...
},

remove: function(){
   this.model.unbind('change:revision', this.render, this);
}

---

Now there is enough context to unbind 'change:revision' for this.render bound to the 'this' variable. When Backbone makes the call it can simply do an apply and pass in the optional third argument.

