Our API needs to be able to handle the IF-Match header.  This is a standard "etag" type header that is used to pass optimistic concurrency information.  Basically, when a PUT or DELETE is called, the tag is set to the version of the record on the client and that is then matched to the server to make sure that the record did not change since the client retrieved it.  If it does, then a 412 status code is supposed to be sent.  While not quite a standard, this is an accepted way of handling optimistic concurrency in REST services.  

PUTs can obviously just pass the correct version in the body of the request.  Put a DELETE request can not.  The IF-Match alleviates the problem.

If this is something to pursue, I have absolutely no idea about the best way of handling it.  I created a fix that was very specific to our needs.  In the Backbone.synch, I simply added the following code to match up a version attribute on the model:

```
    var version = model.get("version");
    if (!isNullOrUndefined(version))
        params.beforeSend = function (xhr) {
            xhr.setRequestHeader("If-Match", version);
        };
```

